you're carrying there?

11:07.067 --> 11:08.867
[amanda] oh, it's an
akonua buck knife.

11:08.869 --> 11:11.670
Was made the year I was born,
so it's my lucky knife.

11:11.672 --> 11:13.672
[rogers] it's a good
looking knife, sharp.

11:18.345 --> 11:20.078
So, I'm making,

11:20.080 --> 11:21.913
like, a hazelnut white rum.

11:21.915 --> 11:23.148
She impressed me pretty good

11:23.150 --> 11:25.016
on the way she
made the hazelnut.

11:25.018 --> 11:26.451
Amanda, buttery notes,

11:26.453 --> 11:28.520
the creamy notes,
it's wonderful.

11:28.522 --> 11:30.488
Amanda is the
next master distiller.

11:30.490 --> 11:31.756
[all applauding]

11:31.758 --> 11:33.091
we got to talking,

11:33.093 --> 11:35.894
<i>  she wants to learn little</i>
<i>  bit about the old ways</i>

11:35.896 --> 11:38.396
<i>  so I thought might do</i>
<i>  a little trading,</i>

11:38.398 --> 11:41.166
teach her how to do some
of the old things

11:41.168 --> 11:42.300
and she might show me

11:42.302 --> 11:43.968
something about
the new things.

11:43.970 --> 11:45.637
-Is this something
you guys made?
-[huck] yeah.

11:45.639 --> 11:47.272
-You wanna try some of that?
-[amanda] I'd love to.

11:47.274 --> 11:48.306
[huck] that's a
stone cold liquor.

11:48.308 --> 11:51.109
I started making liquor
about five years ago.

11:51.111 --> 11:52.877
I'll pour you a little
bit on that cup.

11:52.879 --> 11:54.012
[amanda] thank you.

11:54.014 --> 11:55.547
I basically, fell in
love with the craft

11:55.549 --> 11:56.848
<i>  through the history of it.</i>

11:56.850 --> 11:58.249
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

11:58.251 --> 12:00.051
I'm fascinated by the lengths

12:00.053 --> 12:01.386
that the old timers
went through

12:01.388 --> 12:05.123
to just pay their bills and
take care of their families.

12:05.125 --> 12:07.859
The corn is perfect,
smooth, a little bit sweet.

12:07.861 --> 12:08.993
<i>  With mark and huck,</i>

12:08.995 --> 12:11.429
I feel like, I can really
get a good idea of

12:11.431 --> 12:12.997
how that's done still today.

12:12.999 --> 12:16.000
<i>  'cause they're still doing it</i>
<i>  in the old fashioned way.</i>

12:16.002 --> 12:17.469
[rogers] we'll help
you out all we can.

12:17.471 --> 12:20.171
But you can help us out
on real good flavor later.

12:20.173 --> 12:21.372
It'll sure help.

12:21.374 --> 12:23.308
I'll do my best, I'm pretty
good with playing with flavors

12:23.310 --> 12:25.777
and making liquor that
people like to drink.

12:25.779 --> 12:27.112
[rogers] I'll tell you what
we're gonna do,

12:27.114 --> 12:29.180
we're gonna start you
from the scratch,

12:29.182 --> 12:31.049
we're gonna show you
how to build a furnace.

12:31.051 --> 12:32.417
Early in the spring,

12:32.419 --> 12:34.352
<i>  people buy a whole</i>
<i>  lot of liquor.</i>

12:34.354 --> 12:37.155
So we'd set up
a good easy fix,

12:37.157 --> 12:38.690
you know, before we
get running quick.

12:38.692 --> 12:40.125
-We're gonna use clay.
-Clay.

12:40.127 --> 12:43.027
-You don't use cement,
it'll crack and bust.
-Yes.

12:43.029 --> 12:45.029
Clay is the best
thing you can use.

12:45.031 --> 12:47.298
<i>  Now, I thought it'd</i>
<i>  be a good time to</i>

12:47.300 --> 12:49.134
set us up a rock furnace.

12:49.136 --> 12:51.102
<i> It will help us on later runs.</i>

12:51.104 --> 12:52.203
I love playing with
modern rock,

12:52.205 --> 12:55.039
so I'm super excited about it.

12:55.041 --> 12:57.075
<i> [rogers] I'm getting some</i>
<i>  age on me now,</i>

12:57.077 --> 12:58.977
and amanda, she's young,

12:58.979 --> 13:01.312
<i>  we gotta teach her</i>
<i>  everything we can.</i>

13:01.314 --> 13:02.313
[huck] you'll see
it right there.

13:02.315 --> 13:03.915
This whole ridge is, like,

13:03.917 --> 13:05.850
dig down a little bit
past that topsoil,

13:05.852 --> 13:07.152
so we got good clay.

13:07.154 --> 13:09.888
We gotta keep this
moonshining going on,

13:09.890 --> 13:11.656
even when I'm gone,

13:11.658 --> 13:14.058
<i>  it still needs to</i>
<i>  keep it going.</i>

13:14.060 --> 13:15.827
You wanna do the sifting
or the shoveling?

13:15.829 --> 13:17.061
I'll shovel.

13:17.063 --> 13:19.497
-I'll get the buckets.
-All right.

13:25.105 --> 13:27.839
If you don't sift this
stuff out real good,

13:27.841 --> 13:30.108
you'll have them
big clumps in it.

13:30.110 --> 13:32.010
Can't get your rocks
to lay good,

13:32.012 --> 13:33.845
it's aggravating work.

13:33.847 --> 13:35.480
<i>  Clay, you know,</i>
<i>  is a real package,</i>

13:35.482 --> 13:36.347
<i>  the old timers,</i>

13:36.349 --> 13:38.283
that's what they used to

13:38.285 --> 13:39.984
<i>  chink the cracks</i>
<i>  in their log cabins</i>

13:39.986 --> 13:42.854
and lay the rock for their
chimney, you know.

13:42.856 --> 13:43.988
See, when you sift it out

13:43.990 --> 13:45.957
this about makes it
like powder.

13:45.959 --> 13:47.325
Then when you mix
a little water with it,

13:47.327 --> 13:49.060
you know, it'll be
just like glue.

13:50.096 --> 13:51.796
Amanda, what type
of still you got?

13:51.798 --> 13:53.965
[amanda] I have a 25
gallon copper pot.

13:53.967 --> 13:55.934
Mark and huck are on
a whole different scale

13:55.936 --> 13:57.068
to what I do at home.

13:57.070 --> 13:58.837
<i>  Volume, is something that I'm</i>

13:58.839 --> 14:00.305
<i>  really trying to</i>
<i>  increase right now</i>

14:00.307 --> 14:02.140
and they're experts at it.

14:02.142 --> 14:04.642
Yeah, I use a little
propane burner.

14:04.644 --> 14:06.244
And it could be...
The heat's direct,

14:06.246 --> 14:08.847
so I have to be really careful
about solids in the pot

14:08.849 --> 14:10.148
and scorching the mash.

14:10.150 --> 14:12.083
And that's another benefit
of doing a furnace

14:12.085 --> 14:14.118
'cause it's not
directly on the pot.

14:14.120 --> 14:16.421
You're more or less heating
the sides of the furnace.

14:16.423 --> 14:18.356
-Float them...
-Yeah.

14:19.893 --> 14:22.227
Amanda, I know she's
a good worker,

14:22.229 --> 14:24.696
<i>  she started in</i>
<i>  shoveling that clay</i>

14:24.698 --> 14:27.198
and I know we're in good
shape with her there,

14:27.200 --> 14:29.100
she ain't lazy,
I'll tell you that.

14:29.102 --> 14:30.869
That ought to be enough.

14:30.871 --> 14:32.670
[huck] so, then we'll teach
her how to build a furnace.

14:42.716 --> 14:44.883
[ramsey] if you can get
a barrel hanging out there,

14:44.885 --> 14:46.918
that will be the place for it,
it will swing.

14:46.920 --> 14:48.853
There's a lot of wind that
comes through here.

14:48.855 --> 14:51.256
It's a thought but I don't
think it will work.

14:51.258 --> 14:53.124
I mean, as much
as I'd love to have

14:53.126 --> 14:55.059
whisky barrels
hanging here...

14:55.061 --> 14:56.261
[digger] it ain't feasible.

14:56.263 --> 14:58.196
We'd have to hire a crane.

14:58.198 --> 14:59.964
[ramsey] and what if you
drop one of 'em,

14:59.966 --> 15:02.000
when you're trying
to hang it up.

15:02.002 --> 15:04.068
[digger] you would have
shot yourself in the foot.

15:04.070 --> 15:05.637
<i>  We don't have the</i>
<i>  equipment it'd take</i>

15:05.639 --> 15:08.039
<i>  to put barrels up</i>
<i>  on these rails here.</i>

15:08.041 --> 15:11.142
It's too far off the ground,
we can't do anything with it.

15:11.144 --> 15:12.977
We gotta study
about it a little bit,

15:12.979 --> 15:14.979
how to hoist it up and get it,

15:14.981 --> 15:16.581
get it hanging and moving.

15:16.583 --> 15:17.916
We gotta get it in motion.

15:17.918 --> 15:19.951
We're not gonna be here
babysitting these,

15:19.953 --> 15:21.686
there's no electricity
up here.

15:21.688 --> 15:23.187
<i>  We have to do it naturally</i>

15:23.189 --> 15:26.024
<i>  with the resources that</i>
<i>  mother nature provides.</i>

15:26.026 --> 15:28.326
Hey, puss. Dream catcher.

15:29.963 --> 15:31.062
Huh.

15:31.064 --> 15:33.298
[digger] looks more like
a nightmare to me.

15:33.300 --> 15:36.367
[ramsey] I don't ever
remember riding that. Do you?

15:36.369 --> 15:37.335
No, I don't.

15:37.337 --> 15:39.837
It may have
been put there later.

15:39.839 --> 15:43.241
[digger] looks like exactly
what I was thinking.

15:43.243 --> 15:44.976
[ramsey] let's see if we can--

15:44.978 --> 15:46.844
[digger] that hole there for
the exit, it'll hold a barrel.

15:46.846 --> 15:49.914
[ramsey] oh, my!

15:49.916 --> 15:52.650
The dream catcher's kinda
tilt the world up thing,

15:52.652 --> 15:54.419
it's got little seats that
on their own swivel

15:54.421 --> 15:56.187
<i>  and your chair swings out,</i>

15:56.189 --> 15:58.456
you know, the g-force
makes the chairs

15:58.458 --> 16:00.091
go out as they turn around.

16:00.093 --> 16:01.092
[grunts]

16:03.196 --> 16:04.162
hey.

16:05.498 --> 16:06.497
Look at this.

16:08.034 --> 16:10.468
This might be exactly
what we're looking for.

16:11.304 --> 16:12.937
<i> [ramsey] I can see barrels</i>

16:12.939 --> 16:15.673
<i>  in every one of these.</i>

16:27.153 --> 16:29.320
[mike] here we are, the
wedding day is here.

16:29.322 --> 16:30.688
Champagne's ready.

16:30.690 --> 16:33.391
The bride asked for it
and she got it.

16:33.393 --> 16:35.693
<i>  Me and jenna have been</i>
<i>  engaged for long damn time</i>

16:35.695 --> 16:37.095
<i>  but today is the big day,</i>

16:37.097 --> 16:38.796
<i> we're finally getting married.</i>

16:38.798 --> 16:40.665
<i>  You know, I've been</i>
<i>  married a few times before</i>

16:40.667 --> 16:42.900
<i>  but this is our first time,</i>

16:42.902 --> 16:44.669
and hope, her last time.

16:44.671 --> 16:46.270
<i>  So, everything's</i>
<i>  gotta be perfect,</i>

16:46.272 --> 16:47.405
<i>  you know, for her.</i>

16:49.642 --> 16:51.275
[all exclaiming]

16:51.277 --> 16:54.379
[all cheering]

16:54.381 --> 16:56.447
making the final damn walk.

16:56.449 --> 16:57.849
[all laughing]

16:57.851 --> 16:59.250
I'm happy that
friends and family

16:59.252 --> 17:01.119
and all the guests are coming.

17:01.121 --> 17:02.487
Maybe, the fifth
time's the charm.

17:02.489 --> 17:03.855
I don't know, who knows.

17:03.857 --> 17:05.223
[all laughing]

17:05.225 --> 17:06.357
<i> [mike] got all my grooms here,</i>

17:06.359 --> 17:07.792
everybody is here but jerry.

17:07.794 --> 17:09.293
We're just missing
one guy, man.

17:09.295 --> 17:11.896
One and only,
my partner, jerry benson.

17:11.898 --> 17:13.197
So, don't know
if he's gonna be

17:13.199 --> 17:14.632
able to be here or not today.

17:15.869 --> 17:17.935
We'll just remember him today.

17:17.937 --> 17:19.337
Hope that he gets better.

17:28.348 --> 17:30.048
I think we got 'em
all in one piece.

17:30.050 --> 17:32.183
[rogers] that's one thing you
can't do with harder rock.

17:32.185 --> 17:33.951
<i> [huck] one thing I like</i>
<i>  about stone furnace,</i>

17:33.953 --> 17:35.119
once you get it hot,

17:35.121 --> 17:36.954
it's gonna stay hot
for a long time

17:36.956 --> 17:39.057
<i>  and it takes a lot less wood.</i>

17:39.059 --> 17:41.459
You know, it's a little
more work, fixing one.

17:41.461 --> 17:43.928
But once you
get it fixed right,

17:43.930 --> 17:45.863
it pays off in the long run.

17:45.865 --> 17:47.665
Hand me the pot,
we'll go inside the layer

17:47.667 --> 17:48.666
and get it fixed.

17:48.668 --> 17:50.268
The main thing is
it sits right

17:50.270 --> 17:52.236
and then we're gonna
build around the pot.

17:52.238 --> 17:54.472
We got this black corn maize.

17:54.474 --> 17:56.040
<i>  It work and while</i>
<i>  we're working</i>

17:56.042 --> 17:57.408
<i>  on the build and the furnace</i>

17:57.410 --> 18:00.445
but it's not gonna be this,
like, old traditional whisky.

18:00.447 --> 18:01.179
Pretty solid.

18:01.181 --> 18:02.980
<i> [huck] amanda's gonna help us</i>

18:02.982 --> 18:05.850
<i>  infuse this liquor and turn</i>
<i>  it into something special.</i>

18:05.852 --> 18:08.386
We'll get furnace that's
build tight and everything,

18:08.388 --> 18:09.654
it will be good stuff.

18:09.656 --> 18:11.889
-How's this looking for--
-[rogers] looks good to me.

18:11.891 --> 18:12.957
Peace rock.

18:12.959 --> 18:14.859
[rogers] you wanna
lay the first rock?

18:14.861 --> 18:16.294
Oh, I'd love to.

18:16.296 --> 18:18.796
I've never built a wood
burning furnace before.

18:18.798 --> 18:20.998
About how far out
should we bring it?

18:21.000 --> 18:22.433
-I'd go in closer.
-[amanda] in closer.

18:22.435 --> 18:24.102
But I do work as
a roofer at home

18:24.104 --> 18:25.403
and I do stone masonry work.

18:25.405 --> 18:27.105
-About right there.
-[amanda] oh, okay.

18:27.107 --> 18:29.107
<i>  So, I feel right at home</i>
<i>  with these guys.</i>

18:29.109 --> 18:30.174
I love working hard,

18:30.176 --> 18:31.909
I don't mind getting
my hands dirty.

18:31.911 --> 18:34.011
Now, how close are we
gonna put these stones?

18:34.013 --> 18:35.413
In here, just bud 'em up.

18:35.415 --> 18:37.982
And then we'll fill in
the little gaps with the clay.

18:37.984 --> 18:40.118
Amanda's young,
she's eager to learn.

18:40.120 --> 18:41.085
[amanda] when do you wanna

18:41.087 --> 18:42.186
start putting
the clay in here?

18:42.188 --> 18:43.988
[rogers] well, if you wanna
make us a batch.

18:44.858 --> 18:46.023
She ain't lazy.

18:46.025 --> 18:47.391
I like somebody like that.

18:47.393 --> 18:48.426
Guys, I do have a question.

18:48.428 --> 18:50.094
At home, I'll usually just mix

18:50.096 --> 18:52.897
small portions of cement
'cause it sets.

18:52.899 --> 18:55.666
But this isn't gonna set
until we cook it, right?

18:55.668 --> 18:58.069
-That's right.
-So, I can mix
a good amount of it,

18:58.071 --> 18:59.137
so we have it to work with.

18:59.139 --> 19:01.239
That makes two buggies.

19:07.413 --> 19:10.047
-Can we rest you at minute?
-[amanda] sure, thank you.

19:10.049 --> 19:11.816
When I work with cement

19:11.818 --> 19:13.184
you know,
there's lye in cement,

19:13.186 --> 19:15.052
so you can't get it
on your skin

19:15.054 --> 19:16.654
'cause it literally
eats your skin.

19:16.656 --> 19:18.256
Is that the same
with this clay?

19:18.258 --> 19:19.290
It's not, right?

19:19.292 --> 19:21.058
All it does is
changes color.

19:21.060 --> 19:23.194
[both laugh]

19:23.196 --> 19:24.662
well, I'll be red-handed.

19:24.664 --> 19:26.364
I did bring some gloves

19:26.366 --> 19:27.999
to avoid that.

19:30.803 --> 19:31.936
[rogers grunts]

19:45.151 --> 19:47.385
[amanda] how thick are you
going in between layers now?

19:47.387 --> 19:49.453
-Just enough to seal it.
-[amanda] okay.

19:49.455 --> 19:51.856
This is something that
don't have to be perfect

19:51.858 --> 19:53.891
all it needs to
do is hold heat.

19:53.893 --> 19:56.227
[amanda] I'm kind of a
perfectionist, so I'll keep
that in mind.

19:56.229 --> 19:57.762
[huck] he'd mess up too.

19:57.764 --> 19:59.230
[rogers] no.

19:59.232 --> 20:00.464
[amanda] I like the clay,
it's a lot easier

20:00.466 --> 20:01.799
to work with then cement is.

20:01.801 --> 20:03.367
Amanda, she knows
what she's doing,

20:03.369 --> 20:05.203
you can tell she
has laid rock before.

20:11.044 --> 20:13.010
[all laughing]

20:14.814 --> 20:16.814
[amanda] so, about how far
up do you wanna build,

20:16.816 --> 20:18.282
like, right where
you got it here marked?

20:18.284 --> 20:20.084
-[rogers] yeah.
-[amanda] oh, it's sliding.

20:20.086 --> 20:21.819
[rogers] it is sliding.

20:21.821 --> 20:24.388
Let it settle.

20:25.058 --> 20:26.657
Worry about--
[sighs]

20:27.894 --> 20:28.893
damn, there's one rock

20:28.895 --> 20:30.294
we should have
put in right there.

20:33.299 --> 20:36.100
[amanda] no big deal.
No big deal.

20:37.971 --> 20:40.271
That's a masonry
saying, isn't it?

20:40.273 --> 20:42.740
[huck] look like you got
a damn mess, what happened?

20:42.742 --> 20:44.075
[rogers] son of
a bitch failed.

20:45.345 --> 20:47.278
Believe we're onto something
here handy boy.

20:47.280 --> 20:49.313
-[ramsey] how many
chairs are there?
-[digger] ten.

20:49.315 --> 20:50.881
[ramsey] we've got
enough barrels of liquor

20:50.883 --> 20:52.583
to put one in every chair.

20:52.585 --> 20:53.918
[digger exclaims]

20:53.920 --> 20:55.219
now, watch her go.

20:55.221 --> 20:57.688
[ramsey] we have to
harness the power of wind

20:57.690 --> 20:59.690
to keep our barrels in motion.

20:59.692 --> 21:01.993
We can roll them right
up here on this flat spot,

21:01.995 --> 21:03.794
-advance it forward.
-[digger] yup.

21:03.796 --> 21:05.496
[ramsey] hook 'em up,
move to the next one.

21:05.498 --> 21:07.198
The dream catcher
might be exactly

21:07.200 --> 21:08.966
what we're looking for.

21:08.968 --> 21:11.469
Look at that, if that
right there don't

21:11.471 --> 21:14.238
simulate the motion
of a boat on the ocean,

21:14.240 --> 21:15.873
I don't know what will.

21:15.875 --> 21:17.942
<i>  And this thing</i>
<i>  moves very easy.</i>

21:17.944 --> 21:19.877
And it moves in
every direction

21:19.879 --> 21:21.279
that a boat would.

21:21.281 --> 21:22.947
This is sea aging on dry land.

21:22.949 --> 21:24.348
This goes all over the place.

21:24.350 --> 21:27.385
I think we can make
something work with this.

21:27.387 --> 21:30.154
When you let go, it's gonna
keep going. I mean, watch it.

21:30.923 --> 21:32.690
It will go for a few
shakes on its own

21:32.692 --> 21:33.758
and then that blinker's gonna

21:33.760 --> 21:36.093
keep going in
sides for a while.

21:36.095 --> 21:39.030
<i>  You know, the motion</i>
<i>  with the temperature changes</i>

21:39.032 --> 21:40.264
and the biometric pressure,

21:40.266 --> 21:42.366
it causes that
liquor to turn over.

21:42.368 --> 21:44.268
And it gets more
exposure to wood,

21:44.270 --> 21:46.203
every bit of that liquor
would get exposed to the wood

21:46.205 --> 21:48.406
<i>  quicker than it would</i>
<i>  sitting in the rickhouse,</i>

21:48.408 --> 21:51.208
which magnifies
the aging process.

21:51.210 --> 21:54.178
Just build a sail
out of two-by-fours

21:54.180 --> 21:56.280
and put 'em up there
about four by four,

21:56.282 --> 21:57.214
something like that.

21:57.216 --> 21:58.783
[ramsey] a sail.

21:58.785 --> 22:00.885
-Capital idea, young man.
-[digger] yeah.

22:00.887 --> 22:02.987
If we can get some
sort of sail,

